   Results: There were 213 patients who had PLA: 41 (19.2%) patients had GFPLA and 172 (80.8%) patients had non-GFPLA. The PSM analysis resulted in a total of 108 patients (36 GFPLA and 72 non-GFPLA). Median duration of parenteral antibiotic agents was significantly lower in the GFPLA group (9.5 d vs. 14 d, p = 0.044), but median total duration of antibiotic use was comparable (GFPLA 39 d vs. non-GFPLA 37 d, p = 0.634). Median length of stay (days) did not differ significantly between GFPLA and non-GFPLA (14 vs. 15, p = 0.299). There were no statistically significant differences between GFLPA and non-GFLPA in the need for percutaneous drainage (26/36 (72.2%) vs. 47/72 (65.3%), respectively, p = 0.467) and in-hospital all-cause death (4/36 (11.1%) vs. 7 (9.7%), p = 0.822)
   Conclusions: Outcomes of GFPLA are comparable to those of non-GFPLA in the era of multi-modal care.
